00:02:05.650 --> 00:02:10.920
Anyway, putting the camera to manual let’s
you first control the f-stop, which for now

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:15.389
we’ll assume you want as wide open as the
lens will allow, letting in as much light

00:02:15.389 --> 00:02:16.560
as possible.

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:22.569
From here, DSLRs have a handy dandy feature
that let’s you select what ISO or sensitivity

00:02:22.569 --> 00:02:23.640
you want to shoot at.

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:26.389
Now pay attention, this can get tricky.

00:02:26.389 --> 00:02:31.939
While the lower the f-stop the more light
you get, the HIGHER the ISO the more light

00:02:31.939 --> 00:02:32.959
you get.

00:02:32.959 --> 00:02:38.109
So with the f-stop all the way open, you’ll
likely need to lower the ISO to keep your

00:02:38.109 --> 00:02:39.629
shots from being blown out.

00:02:39.629 --> 00:02:42.359
It’s a simple process, but it will take
some tweaking.

